00:03:20.540 --> 00:03:28.350
observations that arise from the study of
human origins that are worthy to consider

00:03:28.350 --> 00:03:34.380
the context of the human present
and future. I mean, there are many, many

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:38.151
more observations that could be made but,
the use focusing on

00:03:38.151 --> 00:03:41.611
the specific topic of this symposium.

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:49.200
The first is, we examined early on is that
the predecessors they were the adaptations

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:54.980
of our predecessors. Not just their
physical appearances but also their

00:03:54.980 --> 00:04:02.090
behaviors, their ways of life, evolved in
a earth that was trending in particular

00:04:02.090 --> 00:04:09.880
directions toward drying and cooling but
also in a highly dynamic world. A world of

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:15.730
dynamic climates, of dynamic landscapes,
changing resources, changes in social

00:04:15.730 --> 00:04:22.440
surroundings and so on. And so many
aspects of the CARTA mission explore

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:30.230
these areas. Now, that's the first. The
second is that the baseline adaptations of

00:04:30.230 --> 00:04:38.300
our species evolved, embedded in
ecosystems. Embedded in the dynamic

00:04:38.300 --> 00:04:46.410
environments and climates those ancestors
of ours encountered. The fundamental

00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:53.750
charge of paleoanthropology, the study of
human evolution is to understand how human

00:04:53.750 --> 00:05:00.430
qualities, including our capacity for the
diversity of cultural histories that have

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:06.000
unfolded over the past thousands of years
and are, of course, unfolding now.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:13.020
That these qualities have emerged in the
natural world, in or by the processes of

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:18.360
nature. So in other words, the takeaway
message there is that humans are integral

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:23.140
to life, humans are integral to the
history of life and that is inescapable

00:05:23.140 --> 00:05:31.760
and it's inescapable in the anthroposy.
Third, the overarching narrative of human

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:39.760
evolution has significantly changed. It is
a change from a worldview and a story of

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:46.880
how the human lineage came to supposedly
have control and dominion over some

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:53.870
primordial ancestral environment, mastery
of that environment. And it has come about

00:05:53.870 --> 00:05:59.340
through scientific studies, particularly
looking at human origins in its

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:06.090
environmental context to a story of
evolving resilience, adaptability and

00:06:06.090 --> 00:06:12.260
persistent change and the challenges of
survival. With regard to my own research,

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:16.330
I used to see like so many others, Africa,
the place where I do my

00:06:16.330 --> 00:06:24.840
a lot of my field research as the cradle
of human kind. A kind of nurturing image.

00:06:24.840 --> 00:06:32.370
The caldron of human evolution is the term
I now prefer, reflecting the churning

00:06:32.370 --> 00:06:38.400
process that define the line between
survival and extinction in the era of

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:44.010
human origins. The fourth point follows
from the third one. And that is that the

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:51.500
ways of life of our evolutionary ancestors
and cousins have come and gone. Extinction

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:57.420
has involved not only the end of gene
pools and lineages, it has also entailed

00:06:57.420 --> 00:07:04.120
the demise of ways of life. So for
example, a Homo erectus was certainly an

00:07:04.120 --> 00:07:13.460
ancestor of Homo sapiens, the way or ways
of life of Erectus are not longer around.

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:18.040
Out of the minimum of
depending upon whether again this term

00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:24.140
lumper or splitter by how you divide up
the fossil record. But out of the minimum

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:29.620
that most paleoanthropologists recognize
of 18 different homo lineages that had

00:07:29.620 --> 00:07:35.811
significant time depth to them. Only one
lineage, of course our species survives.

00:07:36.270 --> 00:07:41.740
All the other ways of life of earlier
hominance have gone extinct, even though

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:46.741
each species possessed at least some of
the unique distinguishing

00:07:46.741 --> 00:07:48.330
qualities of our species.

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:52.970
Now, I have come across people who have
said, "Yeah. But we are around." And

00:07:52.970 --> 00:08:00.190
that's cool. If anyone sees that as good,
it must involve a very jaded view of

00:08:00.190 --> 00:08:05.600
biodiversity including biodiversity in our
own evolutionary tree. The ways of life of

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:10.860
our ancestors and evolutionary cousins
were sustainable but only for a time, and

00:08:10.860 --> 00:08:17.570
they ultimately came to an end. And fifth
and finally, Homo sapiens lives in the

00:08:17.570 --> 00:08:24.760
world by altering it. It is our survival
mechanism. Even simple interactions with

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:30.090
the environment as we look back through
pre-historic time and making up a stone

00:08:30.090 --> 00:08:35.880
tool, moving resources around the
environment, managing fire, building

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:43.310
shelters, planting a seed to try to secure
food, all of these basic activities change

00:08:43.310 --> 00:08:49.440
the immediate surroundings. And this way
of life essential to all human beings

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:51.681
today no matter where they
live on earth,

00:08:51.681 --> 00:08:54.871
was so successful that it
spread worldwide.

00:08:55.810 --> 00:09:01.800
And so now we find ourselves where the
planetary scales of human influence is

00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:08.690
unquestionable. We have the rapidity of
change in landscape that may be quite

00:09:08.690 --> 00:09:13.330
different from anything that has ever been
experienced before. In evolutionary

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:19.110
