00:43:37.871 --> 00:43:42.141
on forever, which had words like,
subduction zones and things like this.

00:43:42.141 --> 00:43:50.471
It described exactly what happened on that
Christmas day, exactly. And the Washington

00:43:50.471 --> 00:43:56.351
Post science writer said, the only thing
that scientists couldn't say is, "Run. Run

00:43:56.351 --> 00:44:03.830
for your lives!" And I think that what
that communicates to me and I hope to all

00:44:03.830 --> 00:44:11.920
of us is that we won't make progress just
simply, just only by trying to throw

00:44:11.920 --> 00:44:17.471
evidence, throw data at people and expect
them to understand.

00:44:17.471 --> 00:44:22.741
Data is no guarantee for caring.

00:44:22.741 --> 00:44:30.081
And no matter what we argue from a
scientific standpoint, it's no guarantee

00:44:30.081 --> 00:44:37.951
for caring and for acting. And so I am
optimistic partly because we have the

00:44:37.951 --> 00:44:43.341
capacity, not only as scientists but
people involved in society and working

00:44:43.341 --> 00:44:50.941
with young people and people from all
walks of society to activate a moral

00:44:50.941 --> 00:44:57.881
conscience and a societal conscience, that
makes use of the fact that we are

00:44:57.881 --> 00:45:05.141
culturally contingent species. And that
means that we have the ability to make

00:45:05.141 --> 00:45:11.671
choices and that we have the ability to
act in ways that change life and lives and

00:45:11.671 --> 00:45:17.611
our understanding of our relationship to
the planet. Historians can point to much

00:45:17.611 --> 00:45:27.271
like Naomi did to matters of slavery, in
South Africa the end of apartheid, matters

00:45:27.271 --> 00:45:33.551
of with regard to global climate.
The response ultimately

00:45:33.551 --> 00:45:38.151
to the ozone hole and
the end of CFC use.

00:45:38.151 --> 00:45:44.611
And actually the tipping point go to use
the term that Liz Hadley used, the tipping

00:45:44.611 --> 00:45:51.401
point in society and all of those
societies actually took years, just years

00:45:51.401 --> 00:45:56.471
to do. Not 10 years. Of course, there was
a big build up, but it took years to do.

00:45:56.471 --> 00:46:01.000
And I think that we have the possibility
of doing that and developing ethics,

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:06.660
morality, compassion that is joined at the
hip with the science that we presented

00:46:06.660 --> 00:46:15.930
today. And as co-chair, I can only point
out that Charlie was also a member of our

00:46:15.930 --> 00:46:18.341
panel today and so he needs to answer.

